
Project Janus: A Mathematical Framework for Dual-Cognitive Architectures in Real-Time Digital Agents

Author: Ouadi Maakoul


Abstract

This thesis establishes a rigorous mathematical foundation for dual-cognitive architectures that separate reflexive execution from deliberative planning across heterogeneous compute substrates. We introduce Project Janus, a theoretical framework comprising two specialized minds: Janus-Praeter, a fast edge-deployed system for real-time interaction, and Janus-Futurus, a slow cloud-based system for deep reasoning. The core theoretical contribution is a formal model of Latent Supervision, wherein strategic guidance is transmitted as dense vectors rather than symbolic commands, enabling tight coupling without breaking the real-time loop.

We develop four integrated mathematical pillars: (1) an information-theoretic gating mechanism based on the Variational Information Bottleneck, proving that the optimal switching policy emerges from rate-distortion trade-offs; (2) a manifold alignment framework establishing that latent guidance vectors live in a shared semantic space accessible to both minds, with proofs of representational fidelity via bi-Lipschitz embeddings; (3) a Lyapunov stability analysis guaranteeing that the hybrid system converges to goal states despite intermittent cloud interventions; and (4) a regret-theoretic characterization of asynchronous distillation, bounding the rate at which the edge model acquires cloud capabilities.

We prove the Janus Scaling Law, relating edge capacity, cloud query frequency, and task performance, and establish the Optimal Switching Frontier as the rate-distortion curve of the information bottleneck. The four foundational lemmas—Entropy-Gating Lower Bound, Representation Monotonicity, Distillation Convergence under Intermittent Supervision, and Task-Relevant Compression Bound—provide the theoretical bedrock. Finally, we introduce Cognitive Elasticity, demonstrating how the framework adapts to bandwidth and budget constraints while maintaining information-theoretic optimality.

This work establishes the first unified mathematical language for designing real-time digital agents that combine the speed of edge inference with the intelligence of cloud-scale models, with applications spanning UI automation, robotic control, and human-AI collaboration.

