Appendix B: Derivations of Key Formulas

B.1 Derivation of the Variational Information Bottleneck Objective

The Information Bottleneck method seeks a representation Z of X that preserves information about a target variable Y. The objective is to minimize I(X;Z) - \beta I(Z;Y). The variational lower bound (Alemi et al., 2017) is obtained by introducing a variational decoder q(y|z) and a prior r(z):

I(Z;Y) = \int p(y,z) \log \frac{p(y|z)}{p(y)} \, dy\,dz = \int p(y,z) \log \frac{q(y|z)}{p(y)} \, dy\,dz + \int p(z) D_{KL}(p(y|z)\|q(y|z)) \, dz.

The second term is non‑negative, so

I(Z;Y) \ge \int p(y,z) \log q(y|z) \, dy\,dz + H(Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}[\mathbb{E}_{p(z|x)}[\log q(y|z)]] + H(Y).

Similarly,

I(X;Z) = \int p(x,z) \log \frac{p(z|x)}{p(z)} \, dx\,dz = \int p(x,z) \log \frac{p(z|x)}{r(z)} \, dx\,dz + D_{KL}(p(z)\|r(z)) \le \int p(x) D_{KL}(p(z|x)\|r(z)) \, dx,

since the KL divergence is non‑negative. Combining, we obtain the VIB objective:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}} = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)} \left[ \mathbb{E}_{p(z|x)}[-\log q(y|z)] + \beta D_{KL}(p(z|x)\|r(z)) \right].

In the deterministic encoder case (p(z|x) is a Dirac delta), the KL term becomes -\log r(z), and the objective reduces to the rate‑distortion trade‑off.

B.2 Derivation of InfoNCE as a Lower Bound on Mutual Information

The InfoNCE loss (Oord et al., 2018) for a positive pair (x,y) and a set of N-1 negative samples \{y_j\}_{j\neq i} is

\mathcal{L}_{\text{NCE}} = -\mathbb{E}\left[ \log \frac{\exp(\text{sim}(x,y_i))}{\sum_{j=1}^N \exp(\text{sim}(x,y_j))} \right].

We show that the optimal value of this loss is a lower bound on I(X;Y). Let f(x,y) = \exp(\text{sim}(x,y)). The loss is the cross‑entropy for classifying the positive pair among N distractors. The optimal score is proportional to the density ratio p(y|x)/p(y). Plugging this in, the loss becomes

\mathcal{L}_{\text{NCE}}^* = -\mathbb{E}\left[ \log \frac{ \frac{p(y_i|x)}{p(y_i)} }{ \sum_{j=1}^N \frac{p(y_j|x)}{p(y_j)} } \right].

For large N, the denominator approximates N \cdot \mathbb{E}_{p(y)}[p(y|x)/p(y)] = N. Thus

\mathcal{L}_{\text{NCE}}^* \approx -\mathbb{E}\left[ \log \frac{p(y_i|x)}{p(y_i)} \right] + \log N = I(X;Y) + H(Y) + \log N.

Since H(Y) \ge 0, we have I(X;Y) \le \mathcal{L}_{\text{NCE}}^* + \log N. Rearranging gives the bound used in Theorem 5.2.

B.3 Derivation of the Task‑Relevant Rate‑Distortion Function

Let O be the observation, A the optimal action. The goal is to compress O into a representation S such that the cloud's action distribution \pi_f(a|S) is as close as possible to \pi_f(a|O). Define the distortion as

D = \mathbb{E}\left[ D_{KL}(\pi_f(\cdot|O) \| \pi_f(\cdot|S)) \right].

We seek the minimum rate R = I(O;S) achieving distortion \le D. This is a standard rate‑distortion problem with a distortion measure that depends on the cloud model. By the rate‑distortion theorem,

R(D) = \min_{p(s|o): \mathbb{E}[D_{KL}] \le D} I(O;S).

If the cloud model is deterministic (or we consider its internal representation), we can sometimes derive a closed form. In general, this is a variational optimization that can be solved using the Blahut‑Arimoto algorithm or by training a neural encoder with a Lagrange multiplier, as described in Section 3.5.1.

B.4 Derivation of the Lyapunov Drift Inequality

We derive the drift inequality from Theorem 6.5. Let V(s) be a Lyapunov function satisfying \mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t, a_t \sim \pi^*] \le \rho V(s_t) with \rho<1 for the optimal policy. For the Janus policy, which combines local actions and guided actions, we have

\mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t] = (1-p_g) \mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t, \text{local}] + p_g \mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t, \text{guided}],

where p_g = \mathbb{E}[g_t|s_t].

For local actions, the policy \pi_p may be suboptimal. However, we assume that the edge policy is trained to minimize a loss that includes a term encouraging it to follow the optimal policy; as a result, its performance is bounded by \mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t, \text{local}] \le \rho_p V(s_t) with \rho_p \le 1. Typically \rho_p > \rho (worse contraction).

For guided actions, if the guidance were perfect (i.e., the cloud could implement the optimal policy), we would have \mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t, \text{perfect}] \le \rho V(s_t). With alignment error, the actual guided policy incurs an additional term: \mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t, \text{guided}] \le \rho V(s_t) + C \epsilon_{\text{align}}.

Plugging in:

\mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1})|s_t] \le (1-p_g) \rho_p V(s_t) + p_g (\rho V(s_t) + C \epsilon_{\text{align}}) = [(1-p_g)\rho_p + p_g \rho] V(s_t) + p_g C \epsilon_{\text{align}}.

Define \alpha = 1 - [(1-p_g)\rho_p + p_g \rho]. Since \rho_p, \rho < 1, \alpha > 0. Then

\mathbb{E}[V(s_{t+1}) - V(s_t)|s_t] \le -\alpha V(s_t) + p_g C \epsilon_{\text{align}}.

This is the desired drift inequality with \delta_{\text{align}} = p_g C \epsilon_{\text{align}}.

