Appendix C: Technical Lemmas

C.1 Lemma on Smoothness of Neural Network Loss

Lemma C.1. Let f_\theta be a neural network with Lipschitz activations (e.g., ReLU) and bounded weights. Then the loss \ell(\theta) = -\log \pi_p(a|h^k,g,z) is L-smooth in \theta for some L that depends on the network architecture and the data distribution.

Proof. The log‑likelihood is a composition of smooth functions (softmax, cross‑entropy) with the network output. The gradient is bounded and Lipschitz because the network is Lipschitz and the loss has bounded second derivatives. A detailed proof can be found in standard deep learning theory (e.g., Hardt et al., 2016). ∎

C.2 Lemma on Bias‑Variance Decomposition in Distillation

Lemma C.2. The expected excess risk of the distilled model can be decomposed as

\mathbb{E}[\mathcal{L}(\theta_n) - \mathcal{L}(\theta^*)] \le \underbrace{\frac{\sigma^2}{2\mu n}}_{\text{variance}} + \underbrace{\left(1 - \frac{Q^*}{T}\right)^2 B}_{\text{bias}},

where \sigma^2 is the gradient noise variance, \mu is the strong convexity constant, and B is a constant depending on the mismatch between the supervised and unsupervised distributions.

Proof. Follows from the analysis in Appendix A.4. ∎

C.3 Lemma on Spectral Gap and Representation Dimension

Lemma C.3. Let \Sigma be the covariance matrix of the representations in Praeter's latent space. The effective dimension of the action‑relevant subspace is at most the number of eigenvalues of \Sigma that are greater than a threshold \tau. The increase in mutual information when adding a new dimension is proportional to the corresponding eigenvalue.

Proof. This is a standard result from principal component analysis and its application to mutual information. For Gaussian representations, the mutual information between the representation and the action is \frac12 \log \det(I + \Sigma). The contribution of each eigenvalue is additive in the log‑determinant. ∎

